   (Message) I investigated `src/be_vm.c` around the VM opcode handlers and
   traced the failing script `tests/bitwise.be`.
   
   The test contains:
   
   ```berry
   a = 11
   ...
   assert(~a == -12)
   assert(~11 == -12)
   ```
   
   The bytecode reaches the VM `FLIP` opcode for `~a`. At that point the VM
   register holding `a` contains:
   
   ```text
   R1.v.i = 11
   R1.type = BE_INT
   ```
   
   The instruction is the `FLIP` opcode, whose comment in `be_opcodes.h` says:
   
   ```c
   OPCODE(FLIP),       /*  A, B     |   R(A) <- ~RK(B) */
   ```
   
   But the implementation in `src/be_vm.c` is:
   
   ```c
   opcase(FLIP): {
       bvalue *dst = RA(), *a = RKB();
       if (var_isint(a)) {
           var_setint(dst, -a->v.i);
       } else if (var_isinstance(a)) {
           ins_unop(vm, "~", *RKB());
           reg = vm->reg;
           *RA() = *vm->top; /* copy result to dst */
       } else {
           unop_error(vm, "~", a);
       }
       dispatch();
   }
   ```
   
   For integer operands, `FLIP` is using arithmetic negation:
   
   ```c
   -a->v.i
   ```
   
   instead of bitwise complement:
   
   ```c
   ~a->v.i
   ```
   
   So when the test evaluates:
   
   ```berry
   ~11
   ```
   
   the VM computes:
   
   ```text
   -11
   ```
   
   instead of the expected bitwise result:
   
   ```text
   ~11 == -12
   ```
   
   This makes the assertion false. The program does not crash with a signal; it
   runs to completion / exits through the normal libc frames, but the test
   oracle reports incorrect behavior because the interpreter implemented the `~`
   operator incorrectly.
   
   The neighboring `NEG` opcode correctly uses arithmetic negation:
   
   ```c
   opcase(NEG): {
       ...
       if (var_isint(a)) {
           var_setint(dst, -a->v.i);
       }
       ...
   }
   ```
   
   The `FLIP` handler appears to have been copied from `NEG` and not changed for
   the integer case.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: `src/be_vm.c:746` implements the integer `FLIP` / `~` opcode as
   arithmetic negation, `-a->v.i`, instead of bitwise complement, `~a->v.i`.
   Therefore `~11` evaluates to `-11` instead of `-12`, causing
   `tests/bitwise.be` assertions to fail.
   
   LOCAL FIX:
   
   ```diff
   diff --git a/src/be_vm.c b/src/be_vm.c
   --- a/src/be_vm.c
   +++ b/src/be_vm.c
   @@ -743,7 +743,7 @@ static void vm_exec(bvm *vm)
            opcase(FLIP): {
                bvalue *dst = RA(), *a = RKB();
                if (var_isint(a)) {
   -                var_setint(dst, -a->v.i);
   +                var_setint(dst, ~a->v.i);
                } else if (var_isinstance(a)) {
                    ins_unop(vm, "~", *RKB());
                    reg = vm->reg;
   ```
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Avoid hand-written duplicated opcode logic for unary integer
   operators. Introduce a shared helper or macro that makes the intended
   primitive operation explicit and testable, for example:
   
   ```c
   #define int_unop_block(op, opname)                 \
       bvalue *dst = RA(), *a = RKB();                \
       if (var_isint(a)) {                            \
           var_setint(dst, op a->v.i);                \
       } else if (var_isinstance(a)) {                \
           ins_unop(vm, opname, *RKB());              \
           reg = vm->reg;                             \
           *RA() = *vm->top;                          \
       } else {                                       \
           unop_error(vm, opname, a);                 \
       }
   
   opcase(NEG): {
       int_unop_block(-, "-");
       dispatch();
   }
   opcase(FLIP): {
       int_unop_block(~, "~");
       dispatch();
   }
   ```
   
   Also add VM-level regression tests for every primitive unary opcode,
   specifically checking that `~0 == -1`, `~1 == -2`, and `~11 == -12`, so
   copy/paste mistakes between `NEG` and `FLIP` are caught immediately.

